reviews.review: This course is about Software development life cycle. Project teams, documentation, and group dynamics. Software cost estimation. Requirements of engineering and design. Data modeling, object modeling, and object-oriented analysis. Object-oriented programming and design. Software testing and quality assurance. Software maintenance.

Professor Mikkilineni is very knowledgeable about Software Engineering practices. You can tell that she is very passionate about the topic and enjoys passing on her knowledge. Unfortunately, the class is pretty dense with material so it can be quite difficult to take everything in and truly understand it. The class is super slide heavy
Very good professor, take his class! Lot's of practical examples
The professor designed the course in a way to help us adapt easily in the industry. We need to attend his classes as there will be in-class exercises.

Good Professor. In this course there is Broad coverage of ethical issues related to software development. Formal inquiry into normative reasoning in a professional context. Application of ethical theories to workplace issues, viz., cost-benefit analysis, externalities, individual and corporate responsibility, quality and authorship of product. Case studies and in-class topics of debate include computer privacy, encryption, intellectual property, software patents and copyrights, hackers and break-ins, freedom of speech and the internet, error-free code, and liability.
This course will help us in industry

Nice guy who is eager to teach. The course has really useful content, and he does his best to cover everything. He always repeats to make sure you understand. He is patient with questions so If you have trouble understanding something, ask and he will explain in more detail. There is a group project.
